M_LOC[ 229] = "Long Discourses 15";
M_LOC[ 230] = "The Great Discourse on Causation";
M_LOC[ 231] = "1. Dependent Origination";
M_LOC[ 232] = "So I have heard.";
M_LOC[ 233] = "At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Kurus, near the Kuru town named Kammāsadamma.";
M_LOC[ 234] = "When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for continued existence?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’";
M_LOC[ 235] = "If they say, ‘What is a condition for continued existence?’ you should answer, ‘Grasping is a condition for continued existence.’";
M_LOC[ 236] = "When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for grasping?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’";
M_LOC[ 237] = "When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for feeling?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’<br>If they say, ‘What is a condition for feeling?’ you should answer, ‘Contact is a condition for feeling.’";
M_LOC[ 238] = "When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for contact?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’";
M_LOC[ 239] = "If they say, ‘What is a condition for contact?’ you should answer, ‘Name and form are conditions for contact.’";
M_LOC[ 240] = "When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for name and form?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’";
M_LOC[ 241] = "If they say, ‘What is a condition for name and form?’ you should answer, ‘Consciousness is a condition for name and form.’";
M_LOC[ 242] = "When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for consciousness?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’";
M_LOC[ 243] = "‘Continued existence is a condition for rebirth’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.<br>Suppose there were totally and utterly no continued existence for anyone anywhere.<br>That is, continued existence in the sensual realm, the realm of luminous form, or the formless realm. When there’s no continued existence at all, with the cessation of continued existence, would rebirth still be found?”<br>“No, sir.”<br>“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of rebirth, namely continued existence.";
M_LOC[ 244] = "‘Grasping is a condition for continued existence’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.";
M_LOC[ 245] = "Suppose there were totally and utterly no grasping for anyone anywhere.";
M_LOC[ 246] = "‘Feeling is a condition for craving’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.";
M_LOC[ 247] = "Suppose there were totally and utterly no feeling for anyone anywhere.";
M_LOC[ 248] = "That is, feeling born of contact through the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind. When there’s no feeling at all, with the cessation of feeling, would craving still be found?”";
M_LOC[ 249] = "‘Stinginess is a cause of safeguarding’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.";
M_LOC[ 250] = "Suppose there were totally and utterly no stinginess for anyone anywhere. When there’s no stinginess at all, with the cessation of stinginess, would safeguarding still be found?”";
M_LOC[ 251] = "‘Attachment is a cause of possessiveness’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.";
M_LOC[ 252] = "Suppose there were totally and utterly no attachment for anyone anywhere. When there’s no attachment at all, with the cessation of attachment, would possessiveness still be found?”";
M_LOC[ 253] = "‘Assessing is a cause of desire and lust’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.";
M_LOC[ 254] = "Suppose there were totally and utterly no assessing for anyone anywhere. When there’s no assessing at all, with the cessation of assessing, would desire and lust still be found?”";
M_LOC[ 255] = "“No, sir.”";
M_LOC[ 256] = "‘Craving is a cause of seeking’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.";
M_LOC[ 257] = "Suppose there were totally and utterly no craving for anyone anywhere.";
M_LOC[ 258] = "‘Name and form are conditions for contact’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.";
M_LOC[ 259] = "Suppose there were none of the features, attributes, signs, and details by which the category of mental phenomena is found. Would linguistic contact still be found in the category of physical phenomena?”";
M_LOC[ 260] = "“No, sir.”";
M_LOC[ 261] = "“Suppose there were none of the features, attributes, signs, and details by which the category of physical phenomena is found. Would impingement contact still be found in the category of mental phenomena?”";
M_LOC[ 262] = "How do those who describe the self describe it?";
M_LOC[ 263] = "They describe it as physical and limited:";
M_LOC[ 264] = "";
M_LOC[ 265] = "";
M_LOC[ 266] = "";
M_LOC[ 267] = "";
M_LOC[ 268] = "";
M_LOC[ 269] = "Now, take those who don’t describe the self as physical and limited …";
M_LOC[ 270] = "physical and infinite …";
M_LOC[ 271] = "formless and limited …";
M_LOC[ 272] = "formless and infinite.";
M_LOC[ 273] = "They don’t describe the self as formless and infinite in the present; or in some future life; and they don’t think: ‘Though it is not like that, I will ensure it is provided with what it needs to become like that.’";
M_LOC[ 274] = "This being so, it’s appropriate to say that a view of self as formless and infinite doesn’t underlie them.";
M_LOC[ 275] = "That’s how those who don’t describe the self don’t describe it.";
M_LOC[ 276] = "4. Regarding a Self";
M_LOC[ 277] = "How do those who regard the self regard it?";
M_LOC[ 278] = "They regard feeling as self:";
M_LOC[ 279] = "‘Feeling is my self.’";
M_LOC[ 280] = "";
M_LOC[ 281] = "";
M_LOC[ 282] = "Now, regarding these seven planes of consciousness and two dimensions,";
M_LOC[ 283] = "is it appropriate for someone who understands them—and their origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape—to take pleasure in them?”";
M_LOC[ 284] = "“No, sir.”";
M_LOC[ 285] = "When a mendicant enters into and withdraws from these eight liberations—in forward order, in reverse order, and in forward and reverse order—wherever they wish, whenever they wish, and for as long as they wish;";
M_LOC[ 286] = "and when they realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements, they’re called a mendicant who is freed both ways.";
M_LOC[ 287] = "Long Discourses 16<br>The Great Discourse on the Buddha’s Extinguishment<br>So I have heard.";
