M_LOC[ 351] = "Furthermore, an unethical person gets a bad reputation.<br>This is the second drawback.<br>Furthermore, an unethical person enters any kind of assembly timid and embarrassed, whether it’s an assembly of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or ascetics.";
M_LOC[ 352] = "";
M_LOC[ 353] = "";
M_LOC[ 354] = "";
M_LOC[ 355] = "";
M_LOC[ 356] = "There are these five benefits for an ethical person because of their accomplishment in ethics.<br>What five?<br>Firstly, an ethical person gains substantial wealth on account of diligence.<br>This is the first benefit.<br>Furthermore, an ethical person gets a good reputation.";
M_LOC[ 357] = "";
M_LOC[ 358] = "";
M_LOC[ 359] = "";
M_LOC[ 360] = "Furthermore, when an ethical person’s body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.";
M_LOC[ 361] = "This is the fifth benefit.";
M_LOC[ 362] = "These are the five benefits for an ethical person because of their accomplishment in ethics.”";
M_LOC[ 363] = "The Buddha spent most of the night educating, encouraging, firing up, and inspiring the lay followers of Pāṭaligāma with a Dhamma talk. Then he dismissed them,";
M_LOC[ 364] = "“The night is getting late, householders. Please go at your convenience.”";
M_LOC[ 365] = "“Yes, sir,” replied the lay followers of Pāṭaligāma. They got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right, before leaving.";
M_LOC[ 366] = "Soon after they left the Buddha entered a private cubicle.";
M_LOC[ 367] = "and the virtuous here,<br>the restrained spiritual practitioners,";
M_LOC[ 368] = "he should dedicate an offering<br>to the deities there.<br>Venerated, they venerate him;";
M_LOC[ 369] = "";
M_LOC[ 370] = "";
M_LOC[ 371] = "A man beloved of the deities<br>always sees nice things.”";
M_LOC[ 372] = "When the Buddha had expressed his appreciation to Sunidha and Vassakāra with these verses, he got up from his seat and left.<br>Sunidha and Vassakāra followed behind the Buddha, thinking,<br>“The gate through which the ascetic Gotama departs today shall be named the Gotama Gate.<br>The ford at which he crosses the Ganges River shall be named the Gotama Ford.”";
M_LOC[ 373] = "";
M_LOC[ 374] = "";
M_LOC[ 375] = "";
M_LOC[ 376] = "";
M_LOC[ 377] = "";
M_LOC[ 378] = "";
M_LOC[ 379] = "";
M_LOC[ 380] = "";
M_LOC[ 381] = "we have transmigrated for a long time<br>from one rebirth to the next.";
M_LOC[ 382] = "But now that these truths have been seen,<br>the attachment to rebirth is eradicated.";
M_LOC[ 383] = "The root of suffering is cut off,";
M_LOC[ 384] = "now there are no more future lives.”";
M_LOC[ 385] = "And while staying at Koṭigāma, too, the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:";
M_LOC[ 386] = "“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.";
M_LOC[ 387] = "When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.";
M_LOC[ 388] = "When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.";
M_LOC[ 389] = "When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,";
M_LOC[ 390] = "the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”";
M_LOC[ 391] = "9. The Deaths in Nādika";
M_LOC[ 392] = "When the Buddha had stayed in Koṭigāma as long as he wished, he said to Ānanda,";
M_LOC[ 393] = "“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Nādika.”";
M_LOC[ 394] = "And a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.";
M_LOC[ 395] = "This is that mirror of the teaching.”";
M_LOC[ 396] = "And while staying there in Nādika the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:";
M_LOC[ 397] = "“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.";
M_LOC[ 398] = "When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.";
M_LOC[ 399] = "When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.";
M_LOC[ 400] = "And how is a mendicant aware?";
M_LOC[ 401] = "It’s when a mendicant acts with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.";
M_LOC[ 402] = "That’s how a mendicant is aware.";
M_LOC[ 403] = "A mendicant should live mindful and aware.";
M_LOC[ 404] = "This is my instruction to you.”";
M_LOC[ 405] = "11. Ambapālī the Courtesan";
M_LOC[ 406] = "Ambapālī the courtesan heard that the Buddha had arrived and was staying in her mango grove.";
M_LOC[ 407] = "";
M_LOC[ 408] = "After the Buddha had commenced the rainy season residence, he fell severely ill, struck by dreadful pains, close to death.<br>But he endured with mindfulness and situational awareness, without worrying.<br>Then it occurred to the Buddha,<br>“It would not be appropriate for me to become fully extinguished before informing my attendants and taking leave of the mendicant Saṅgha.<br>Why don’t I forcefully suppress this illness, stabilize the life force, and live on?”<br>So that is what he did.<br>Then the Buddha’s illness died down.<br>Soon after the Buddha had recovered from that sickness, he came out from his dwelling and sat in the shade of the porch on the seat spread out.<br>Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,<br>“Sir, it’s fantastic that the Buddha is comfortable and well.<br>Because when the Buddha was sick, my body felt like it was drugged. I was disorientated, and the teachings weren’t clear to me.<br>Still, at least I was consoled by the thought that<br>the Buddha won’t become fully extinguished without making some statement regarding the Saṅgha of mendicants.”<br>“But what could the mendicant Saṅgha expect from me, Ānanda?";
M_LOC[ 409] = "";
M_LOC[ 410] = "";
M_LOC[ 411] = "";
M_LOC[ 412] = "";
